    <section id="section-1">
      <h2>What is lead generation?</h2>

      <p>Lead generation begins with a fundamental question every business must answer: who are the people most likely to buy from us, and how do we get in front of them before a competitor does?</p>

      <p>In marketing, a "lead" is a person or organization that has expressed interest in what you sell — typically by sharing their contact information through a form, a signup page, or a direct inquiry. That action, however small, marks a shift from anonymous visitor to identifiable prospect. Lead generation is the systematic process of creating those moments of interest at scale.</p>

      <p><a href="https://business.adobe.com/blog/basics/lead-generation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Adobe defines lead generation</a> as "the process of attracting and nurturing potential customers who show interest in your brand's products or services." <a href="https://www.salesforce.com/marketing/lead-generation-guide/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Salesforce describes it</a> as "the process of building interest in a product or service, then turning that interest into a sale."</p>

      <p>Both definitions share the same through-line: lead generation is not about selling. It is about identifying who might want to buy, and getting them into a position where a conversation — or a direct purchase — can happen naturally.</p>

      <p>A critical distinction that trips up beginners: generating a lead is not the same as acquiring a customer. Most businesses treat lead generation as the first structured stage of a longer customer acquisition journey. The lead comes in; qualification, nurturing, and sales conversion follow.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="section-2">
      <h2>Where does lead generation come from?</h2>

<p>Lead generation predates digital marketing by decades. In its pre-internet form, it was insurance agents building prospect lists from church directories, salespeople collecting business cards at trade shows, and direct-mail marketers renting postal lists by ZIP code and buying mailing lists from publishers.</p>

<p>The telephone expanded lead generation's reach in the mid-20th century. Telemarketing became a profession. Trade shows grew into major B2B lead channels throughout the 1960s and 1980s. The "lead card" — a physical card filled out by a prospect at an event or in response to a print ad — was a standard artifact in sales offices for decades.</p>

<p>The internet changed the economics completely. In the 1990s, early websites began collecting email addresses through subscription forms. By the early 2000s, search engine optimization and pay-per-click advertising allowed businesses to intercept prospects exactly when they were searching for solutions. <a href="https://advertising.amazon.com/library/guides/lead-generation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Amazon Ads notes</a> that today, digital channels have become the primary arena for lead generation across virtually every industry.</p>

<p>The 2010s brought a structural shift: the rise of content marketing, marketing automation platforms, and social media advertising. Lead generation became a measurable, optimizable discipline with its own job titles, toolstack, and performance benchmarks. An entire industry of specialized agencies, software companies, and training platforms emerged to serve the demand.</p>

<p>Today, AI is reshaping lead generation again. Sixty-one percent of B2B teams now use AI for lead scoring — up from just 23% in 2024. Predictive models identify likely buyers before they raise their hands. The core discipline remains the same; the tools keep changing.</p>

    </section>

    <section id="section-3">
      <h2>What are the main types of lead generation?</h2>

<p>Lead generation splits along two fundamental axes: the direction of outreach (inbound vs. outbound), and the degree of qualification (raw lead vs. MQL vs. SQL).</p>

<p><strong>Inbound lead generation</strong> attracts prospects to you. A potential customer searches Google, finds your article, downloads a resource in exchange for their email address, and enters your pipeline. You did not interrupt them — they came to you because your content solved a problem they already had. Ryan Robinson, Founder and CEO of RightBlogger, captures the principle: "Content marketing and SEO teams should attract leads who are already interested in an offering, rather than interrupting people with disruptive ads."</p>

<p><strong>Outbound lead generation</strong> involves reaching out to people who have not yet signalled intent. Cold emails, paid ads targeting cold audiences, <a href="https://olsp.profitandprivilege.com/reviews/olsp-solo-ads/">solo ad campaigns</a>, and trade show outreach are outbound tactics. Response rates are lower, but outbound can reach segments that inbound never touches.</p>

<p>Both approaches feed prospects into a qualification system. The standard framework moves through four stages:</p>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Lead Type</th><th>Definition</th><th>Next Step</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Raw Lead</strong></td><td>Shared contact info but has not been evaluated for fit</td><td>Enter an automated nurture sequence</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>MQL</strong> (Marketing Qualified Lead)</td><td>Fits the ideal customer profile and has taken meaningful engagement actions — downloaded content, attended a webinar, revisited key pages</td><td>Escalate to lead scoring or marketing automation</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>SQL</strong> (Sales Qualified Lead)</td><td>Vetted by a sales representative as having confirmed need, budget, and authority to make a purchase</td><td>Begin a direct sales conversation</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>PQL</strong> (Product Qualified Lead)</td><td>Has used a free or trial version of the product and demonstrated measurable intent signals within the product itself</td><td>Route to account conversion or expansion offer</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>Understanding the MQL/SQL distinction prevents qualified prospects from falling through the cracks between marketing and sales teams — one of the most common and expensive breakdowns in B2B revenue operations. Companies that follow up with MQLs within the first hour achieve a 53% SQL conversion rate, compared to just 17% for follow-ups made after 24 hours.</p>

    </section>

