    <section id="section-8">
      <h2>What goes wrong with lead generation?</h2>

<p>The most damaging lead generation failures are not technical; they are strategic. These four mistakes destroy most lead generation programs before they have a chance to compound.</p>

<p><strong>1. Optimizing for quantity over quality.</strong> Sixty-eight percent of B2B marketers identify improving lead quality — not increasing lead volume — as their top priority. This is because so many campaigns have been optimized for raw lead counts at the expense of fit. Seventy-nine percent of leads never convert to sales, and the primary reason is not a sales problem — it is a lead generation targeting problem. A tool that generates 1,000 low-quality leads per month delivers worse results than one that generates 50 high-quality leads.</p>

<p><strong>2. Slow or no follow-up.</strong> Leads go cold with startling speed. Businesses that follow up within five minutes of lead capture are 9× more likely to convert than those that wait 30 minutes or longer. Yet 42% of sales reps report being too busy for timely follow-up. The fix is simple: automate the first response. The first email in a lead nurture sequence should fire within minutes of form submission, not hours.</p>

<p><strong>3. No structured nurturing strategy.</strong> Most leads are not ready to buy today. Research consistently shows 42% of businesses have no efficient lead nurturing process — meaning captured leads are either ignored or forwarded to sales prematurely. Companies that implement structured lead nurturing generate 50% more sales-ready leads at 33% lower cost. The investment required is a well-written email sequence; the payoff is compounding conversion improvement over months.</p>

<p><strong>4. Misaligned marketing and sales teams.</strong> When marketing passes leads that sales considers unqualified, resentment builds and leads get ignored. The most successful lead generation operations have explicit, documented definitions for MQL and SQL, agreed on by both teams, plus service level agreements governing how quickly sales must follow up on SQLs. This alignment is not a soft management issue — it is a revenue issue.</p>

    </section>

